OUtliers Treatment:¶
In [10]:
#Finding Outliers
q1 = clean_concrete.quantile(0.25)
q3 = clean_concrete.quantile(0.75)
IQR = q3-q1
cwo = ((clean_concrete.iloc[:] < (q1-1.5 * IQR)) | (clean_concrete.iloc[:] > (q3+1.5*IQR))).sum(axis = 0)
outlier_df = pd.DataFrame(cwo, index = clean_concrete.columns, columns = ['No. of Outliers'])
outlier_df['Percentage Outliers'] = round(outlier_df['No. of Outliers'] * 100 / len(concrete_df), 2)
print(outlier_df)

# Handling Outliers using IQR method
clean_concrete2 = clean_concrete.copy()
def handle_outlier(df_in, col_name):
    q1 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1 #Interquartile range
    fence_low  = q1-1.5*iqr
    fence_high = q3+1.5*iqr
    df_in.loc[df_in[col_name] > fence_high, col_name] = df_in[col_name].median()
    df_in.loc[(df_in[col_name] < fence_low), col_name] = df_in[col_name].median()
    return df_in
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'cement')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'slag')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'ash')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'water')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'superplastic')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'coarseagg')
clean_concrete2 = handle_outlier(clean_concrete2, 'fineagg')
clean_concrete2['age'] = clean_concrete2['age']
clean_concrete2['strength'] = clean_concrete2['strength']

Dealing with age attibute: Grouping values to obtain better results¶
In [30]:
new_concrete = clean_concrete2.copy()
#Binning days to months
def label(clean_concrete2):
    if clean_concrete2["age"] <= 30:
        return 1
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 30 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 60 :
        return 2
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 60 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 90 :
        return 3
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 90 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 120 :
        return 4
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 120 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 150 :
        return 5
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 150 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 180 :
        return 6
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 180 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 210 :
        return 7
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 210 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 240 :
        return 8
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 240 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 270 :
        return 9
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 270 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 300 :
        return 10
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 300 and clean_concrete2["age"] <= 330 :
        return 11
    if clean_concrete2["age"] > 330 :
        return 12
new_concrete["age_months"] = clean_concrete2.apply(lambda clean_concrete2:label(clean_concrete2) , axis=1)
new_concrete.drop(['age'], axis = 1)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
pca = PCA().fit(X_scaled)
#Plotting the Cumulative Summation of the Explained Variance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.ylabel('Variance (%)') #for each component
plt.title('Cement Dataset Explained Variance')
plt.show()
This plot tells us that selecting 4 components we can preserve something around 96% of the total variance of the data.¶
It makes sense, we’ll not use 100% of our variance, because it denotes all components, and we want only the principal ones.¶
With this information in our hands, we can implement the PCA for 5 best components by using this snippet of code:¶

In [73]:
#We will save the model performance metrics in a DataFrame
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score
import numpy as np
Model = []
RMSE = []
R_sq = []
cv = KFold(5, random_state = 1)

#Creating a Function to append the cross validation scores of the algorithms
def input_scores(name, model, x, y):
    Model.append(name)
    RMSE.append(np.sqrt((-1) * cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, 
                                               scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean()))
    R_sq.append(cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, scoring='r2').mean())
In [74]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, Ridge, Lasso
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import (RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor, AdaBoostRegressor)

names = ['Linear Regression', 'Ridge Regression', 'Lasso Regression',
         'K Neighbors Regressor', 'Decision Tree Regressor', 
         'Random Forest Regressor', 'Gradient Boosting Regressor',
         'Adaboost Regressor']
models = [LinearRegression(), Ridge(), Lasso(),
          KNeighborsRegressor(), DecisionTreeRegressor(),
          RandomForestRegressor(), GradientBoostingRegressor(), 
          AdaBoostRegressor()]

#Running all algorithms
for name, model in zip(names, models):
    input_scores(name, model, X_train, y_train)
